<% content_for :title, "About SPARC" %>

<div class="card mb-4">
  <div class="card-body">

    <%# ── Hero Section ── %>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
      <%= image_tag "sparc_logo.jpg", alt: "SPARC", style: "height: 120px; width: auto;" %>
      <h1 class="h2 fw-bold mt-3">About SPARC</h1>
      <p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto;">
        Systematic Policy and Regulatory Controls &mdash; a platform for authoring,
        validating, and managing OSCAL-based compliance artifacts with automation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr class="my-4">

    <%# ── Section 1: What is SPARC? ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">What is SPARC?</h2>
      <p>
        SPARC helps organizations centralize, track, and operationalize NIST SP 800-53 security controls
        across the full Risk Management Framework (RMF) lifecycle. It bridges the gap between manual
        compliance workflows and full automation by providing a web interface and REST API for managing
        catalogs, baselines, system security plans, assessments, and evidence &mdash; all in
        machine-readable OSCAL format.
      </p>
      <p>
        Whether you are preparing a FedRAMP authorization package, maintaining an ongoing ATO, or
        tailoring baselines for a new environment, SPARC provides the tools to do it faster with
        fewer errors and complete audit traceability.
      </p>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 2: OSCAL Framework Layers ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">OSCAL Framework Layers</h2>
      <p>
        The Open Security Controls Assessment Language (OSCAL) is a NIST-developed standard for
        expressing security controls, assessment plans, and compliance results in machine-readable
        formats. OSCAL organizes compliance artifacts into layers:
      </p>

      <div class="row g-3 my-3">
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100" style="border-left: 4px solid #3498db;">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold" style="color: #3498db;">Controls Layer</h5>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Catalogs</strong> &mdash; complete sets of security controls (e.g., NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5)</p>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Profiles</strong> &mdash; tailored baselines selecting specific controls (e.g., FedRAMP HIGH)</p>
              <p class="mb-0"><strong>Mappings</strong> &mdash; cross-references between control frameworks</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100" style="border-left: 4px solid #27ae60;">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold" style="color: #27ae60;">Implementation Layer</h5>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>System Security Plans (SSPs)</strong> &mdash; describe how controls are implemented in a system</p>
              <p class="mb-0"><strong>Component Definitions (CDEFs)</strong> &mdash; reusable control implementations for specific technologies</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100" style="border-left: 4px solid #e67e22;">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold" style="color: #e67e22;">Assessment Layer</h5>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Assessment Plans (SAPs)</strong> &mdash; define how security controls will be tested</p>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Assessment Results (SARs)</strong> &mdash; findings from control assessments</p>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Evidence</strong> &mdash; artifacts supporting control assessment findings</p>
              <p class="mb-0"><strong>Plans of Action &amp; Milestones (POA&amp;Ms)</strong> &mdash; track remediation of findings</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100" style="border-left: 4px solid #9b59b6;">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold" style="color: #9b59b6;">Enterprise Layer</h5>
              <p class="mb-1"><strong>Organizations</strong> &mdash; top-level organizational units</p>
              <p class="mb-0"><strong>Authorization Boundaries</strong> &mdash; define the scope of systems under assessment</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        SPARC provides full support across all layers &mdash; from importing NIST catalogs and tailoring
        baselines to generating SSPs, managing assessments, and exporting OSCAL-compliant artifacts in
        JSON, YAML, and XML formats.
      </p>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 3: FedRAMP 20x and OSCAL ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">FedRAMP 20x and OSCAL</h2>
      <p>
        FedRAMP 20x is an initiative to modernize cloud security authorizations through automation
        and machine-readable compliance. Instead of narrative-heavy documentation reviewed manually,
        FedRAMP 20x emphasizes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Machine-readable artifacts</strong> &mdash; OSCAL-based SSPs, SARs, and POA&amp;Ms that can be validated automatically</li>
        <li><strong>Key Security Indicators (KSIs)</strong> &mdash; measurable, outcome-focused security metrics for continuous monitoring</li>
        <li><strong>Continuous assurance</strong> &mdash; ongoing validation replacing periodic point-in-time assessments</li>
        <li><strong>Automated validation</strong> &mdash; targeting 80%+ of control checks via machine-readable evidence</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        SPARC supports both traditional NIST SP 800-53 authorization workflows and the emerging FedRAMP 20x
        model, including a complete KSI catalog with 56 indicators across 11 security themes and validation
        tracking per authorization boundary.
      </p>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 4: SPARC and the Authoritative Layer ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">The Authoritative Layer</h2>
      <p>
        In compliance workflows, the <strong>authoritative layer</strong> is the single source of truth
        for security controls, implementations, and evidence. SPARC serves as this authoritative layer by:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ingesting and validating OSCAL artifacts against NIST schemas</li>
        <li>Generating and maintaining authoritative SSPs, component definitions, and profiles</li>
        <li>Providing centralized storage and versioning of all compliance artifacts</li>
        <li>Enforcing traceability from controls to implementations to assessment findings</li>
        <li>Supporting audit-readiness with complete change tracking and export capabilities</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Every artifact in SPARC is machine-enforceable &mdash; not a static document, but a living data
        structure that can be validated, exported, and integrated into automated compliance pipelines.
      </p>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 5: Automated Validations with MITRE SAF ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">Automated Validations with MITRE SAF</h2>
      <p>
        SPARC integrates with the
        <a href="https://saf.mitre.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-primary">MITRE Security Automation Framework (SAF)</a>
        to provide automated compliance validation:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Schema validation</strong> &mdash; verify OSCAL artifacts conform to NIST schemas (v1.1.2)</li>
        <li><strong>Business-rule checking</strong> &mdash; enforce organizational constraints and FedRAMP requirements</li>
        <li><strong>Control implementation verification</strong> &mdash; validate that implementations address required controls</li>
        <li><strong>XCCDF and HDF support</strong> &mdash; natively import DISA STIGs (XCCDF) and InSpec/HDF results for automated evidence collection</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Automated validations catch issues early, reduce remediation time, and provide confidence
        that authorization packages meet requirements before submission.
      </p>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 6: Control Mappings and Converters ── %>
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">Control Mappings and Converters</h2>
      <p>
        SPARC provides cross-framework control mapping using OSCAL's native mapping schema,
        enabling organizations to maintain compliance across multiple standards simultaneously:
      </p>
      <div class="row g-3 my-3">
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold">Control Mappings</h5>
              <p class="mb-1">Map controls between frameworks using OSCAL's mapping model</p>
              <ul class="mb-0 small">
                <li>NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5 to FedRAMP baselines</li>
                <li>CIS Benchmarks to NIST 800-53</li>
                <li>Custom framework mappings</li>
                <li>KSI-to-NIST control cross-references</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="fw-bold">Automatic Converters</h5>
              <p class="mb-1">Import from multiple source formats automatically</p>
              <ul class="mb-0 small">
                <li>DISA SV/V and CCI identifiers to NIST 800-53</li>
                <li>CIS Benchmarks to NIST 800-53</li>
                <li>XCCDF/SCAP/OVAL results to OSCAL</li>
                <li>InSpec HDF profiles to component definitions</li>
                <li>Excel SSP/SAR templates to OSCAL JSON</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <%# ── Section 7: Get Started ── %>
    <section>
      <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--sparc-primary);">Get Started</h2>
      <div class="row g-3">
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="card h-100 text-center">
            <div class="card-body">
              <div style="font-size: 2.5rem;">&#128214;</div>
              <h5 class="fw-bold mt-2">API Documentation</h5>
              <p class="small text-body-secondary">REST API reference with configurable auth modes (local, OIDC, hybrid) for flexible deployment scenarios.</p>
              <%= link_to "View API Docs", about_api_path, class: "btn btn-primary btn-sm" %>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="card h-100 text-center">
            <div class="card-body">
              <div style="font-size: 2.5rem;">&#128640;</div>
              <h5 class="fw-bold mt-2">Quick-Start Guide</h5>
              <p class="small text-body-secondary">Get up and running with SPARC in minutes &mdash; from installation to your first SSP.</p>
              <%= link_to "Quick Start", about_quickstart_path, class: "btn btn-success btn-sm" %>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="card h-100 text-center">
            <div class="card-body">
              <div style="font-size: 2.5rem;">&#128187;</div>
              <h5 class="fw-bold mt-2">Source Code</h5>
              <p class="small text-body-secondary">SPARC is open source. Explore the codebase, file issues, and contribute.</p>
              <a href="https://github.com/Rebel-Raiders/sparc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="btn btn-outline-primary btn-sm">GitHub Repo</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <% if SparcConfig.contact_email.present? %>
        <div class="text-center mt-4">
          <p class="text-body-secondary small">
            Questions? Contact us at
            <%= mail_to SparcConfig.contact_email, SparcConfig.contact_email, class: "text-primary text-decoration-none" %>
          </p>
        </div>
      <% end %>
    </section>

  </div>
</div>
